indicator.description:
1. # of community organisations proactive in the local planning process with appropriate legal status, availability of sustainability fund, community development plan;

2. # of community members  and local officials trained on participatory decision making;

3. # of replication of CBA methodology in non-CBA territory;

4. # of rayon authorities using LDF for participatory decision making;

5. # of community development plans incorporated in the local development plan;

6. # of regional development funds (RDF) established to support community initiatives;

7. # of community initiatives for improving basic social and communal infrastructure and services supported;

8. # of agro-based service cooperatives to promote small businesses  established.

baseline.comment:
1. Less than 5% of Ukrainian communities have their own community based organisation capable to undertake local development in partnership with local authorities;
2.Most of local officials and local communities in Ukraine lack knowledge on participatory approach to local development;
3. Rayon and regional authorities do not have experience in implementing principles and methodology promoted by CBA on their own;
4. Less than 45% of rayons are experienced in using LDF;
5. Less than 5% of Ukrainian communities experienced in getting their CDPs approved at rayon level;
6. At this moment there is no regional development fund to promote community based local development approach in the country and communal infrastructures in rural areas are poorly maintained;
7. Number of communities applying community based approach for service delivery in Ukraine is negligible;
8. Small producers across in rural Ukraine lack access to market and processing facilities.

target.comment:
1) 4 community organizations established
2) 200 community members and at least 20 local authorities are trained on participatory decision making
3) at least 30 cases of the replication of the CBA methodology in non-CBA territory;
4) Target was 0; Completed in 2013
5) Target was 0; Completed in 2013
6) at least 12 regional development funds (RDF) established to support community initiatives;

actual.comment:
1) 4 new community organizations were established
2) 237 community members and 27 local authorities were trained on the CBA trainings;
3) 30 rayons replicated the CBA methodology  in non CBA territory
4)Target was 0; Completed in 2013 
5) Target was 0; Completed in 2013
6) 12 regional development funds were established to support community initiatives;

2.1. 3 mid-sized regional prospective CSOs hubs in the area of human rights  selected, OD plans elaborated, GAs signed, OD plans implementation launched in the area of human rights upon completion of their tailored organizational development plans;
2.2. 19 CSO projects successfully launched; 15 CSO project successfully completed;
2.3. At least 13 505 individuals benefited from CSOs projects;
2.4. 4 shadow reports supported within Ukraine's international human rights commitments;
2.5. OO-civil society cooperation intensified and analytical and monitoring capacities of the OO enhanced through 4 completed and 3 successfully launched joint CSO projects;  and quality of OO-civil cooperation (measured by # of joint initiatives). 3 joint side events on human rights situation in Ukraine conducted; info session for Diplomatic Corps in Ukraine on 6 months of Crimea occupation conducted; planning workshop and study tour to Georgia to learn about National Human Rights Strategy development and adoption conducted.

2.1. 

-2 CSO hubs - human rights (2) - implemented 70% of their Capacity Development Plans, focusing on two capacities/indicators: i) membership, constituency, volunteerism, and ii) advocacy;
- All 2 hubs rebooted their Boards according to democratic principles; doubled their budgets using local fundraising and good planning; improved their management and procurement procedures; became more open and transparent in their respective communities;
- Number of volunteers increased; each hub implemented two advocacy campaigns in their regions;
- 3 workshops on CDP implementation, report writing, democratic governance.
2.2. 11 CSO projects successfully launched; 15 CSO project successfully completed;
2.3. At least 7000 individuals benefited from CSOs projects;
2.4. 3 shadow reports supported within Ukraine's international human rights commitments;
